<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="436" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1436,261,647]" pageId="3" pageNumber="436">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,335,406,431]" pageId="3" pageNumber="436">Comments.</emphasis>
This widely distributed species can be readily recognized by the presence of an ocular canthi (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1970,1992]" captionTargetBox="[157,1429,705,1941]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[151,1436,702,1948]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2. Dorsal habitus of male. A. Batrisus sibiricus. B. Batriscenellus orientalis. Scale bars: 0.5 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/345822/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="436">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
A), a complete marginal carina extending from the subhumeral fovea at side of the elytra, antennomeres XI with a small ventral denticle, mesotibiae with a distinct apical spine in the male, and most importantly, the endophallus of the symmetric and robust aedeagus composed of a pair of elongate lateral sclerites (
<figureCitation box="[1089,1155,514,539]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1902,1924]" captionTargetBox="[165,1409,193,1848]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[165,1409,193,1859]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 3. Diagnostic features of species (A, D, E – G. Batriscenellus xijiaogongyuan. B – C, H – I. Physomerinus pedator. J. Batrisus sibiricus). A – B. Head and pronotum. C. Metafemur. D. Abdominal tergite IV. E, H. Aedeagus, in lateral view. F, I. Aedeagus, in ventral view. G. Aedeagus, in axial view. J. Aedeagus, in dorsal view. Scales bars: 0.2 mm in A – D, 0.1 mm in E – J." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/345823/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="436">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
J; 
<bibRefCitation author="Besuchet" box="[1181,1350,514,539]" pageId="3" pageNumber="436" refString="Besuchet, C. (1979) Description d'un nouveau Batrisus Aube (Coleoptera, Pselaphidae). Revue Suisse de Zoologie, 86 (1), 279 - 283." type="journal article" year="1979">Besuchet 1979</bibRefCitation>
, fig. 2). According to 
<bibRefCitation author="Besuchet" box="[305,545,550,575]" pageId="3" pageNumber="436" refString="Besuchet, C. (1979) Description d'un nouveau Batrisus Aube (Coleoptera, Pselaphidae). Revue Suisse de Zoologie, 86 (1), 279 - 283." type="journal article" year="1979">Besuchet (1979: 283)</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation author="Nomura" box="[600,879,550,575]" pageId="3" pageNumber="436" refString="Nomura, S. &amp; Lee, C. E. (1993) A revision of the family Pselaphidae (Coleoptera) from South Korea. Esakia, 33, 1 - 48." type="journal article" year="1993">Nomura &amp; Lee (1993: 5)</bibRefCitation>
this species has been associated with 
<taxonomicName box="[1304,1378,551,574]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Lasius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="436" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1304,1378,551,574]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="436">Lasius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
ants. The single male from 
<collectingRegion box="[401,505,586,611]" country="China" name="Shanghai" pageId="3" pageNumber="436">Shanghai</collectingRegion>
was collected under a stone with ants (
<figureCitation box="[951,1019,586,611]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1937,1959]" captionTargetBox="[167,1411,700,1908]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[167,1411,700,1908]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 4. Collecting sites and habitats of the Pselaphinae in Shanghai. A. Collecting sites of Batriscenellus xijiaogongyuan (1), Batrisus sibiricus (2), Physomerinus pedator (3), and Batriscenellus orientalis (4). B. Habitat of Batriscenellus xijiaogongyuan. C. Habitat of Physomerinus pedator." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/345824/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="436">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
A), unfortunately no specimen of the ant was collected.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
